@node FAQs
@{b}Q. Is there a ZX81 emulator for the Amiga?@{ub}

Yes!  Paul Hill has ported the Linux ZX81 emulator "xz81" over to the Amiga.
It's not the best ZX81 emulator on the planet, but most programs work
without problems.  It can also run ZX80 stuff (though quite badly).

If you have OS4, then I have ported PSPZX81 over to that.  It's a ZX81
emulator for the PSP (yes, really!), with most of the PSP gubbins taken
back out.  This leaves us with a nicely portable version of z81, which
is what PSPZX81 was based on.

@{b}Q. Where can I get it from?@{ub}

Paul Hill's website at http://www.lagernet.clara.co.uk/ (dead link)
Aminet at http://www.aminet.net/package/misc/emu/pspzx81

@{b}Q. Okay, the emulator appears to work.  But what about ZX81 software?@{ub}

There are currently two FTP archives of ZX81 software, and quite a few web
pages with small amounts of software to download.  The best place to go to
is World Of Spectrum (WOS) - possibly due for a name change sometime soon!

Alternatively, Carlo Delhez sells packs of games on disk for his Xtender
ZX81 emulator.  These (should) work fine with z81.

Carlo Delhez/Xtender: http://www.delhez.demon.nl
NVG ZX81 section:     ftp://ftp.nvg.ntnu.no/pub/sinclair/zx81
WOS ZX81 section:     ftp://ftp.worldofspectrum.org/pub/zx81
ZX81.NL               http://www.zx81.nl

WOS also has a web page: http://www.worldofspectrum.org

The Sinclair InfoSeek search engine on there
[http://www.worldofspectrum.org/infoseek.cgi] has the ability to search for
the following ZX81 material:

NVG program files (by name and filename)
WOS program files (by title and filename only)
Sinclair User type-in listings (SPOT*ON database)

At the time of writing, the WOS ZX81 index is nearly finished.  There is
an alternative search engine for the data at
http://www.unsatisfactory.freeserve.co.uk/zx81search/

There are also plans to index all the ZX81 type-in listings, which will
display results similar to the SPOT*ON database but include more (ZX81
related) magazines, and indexes to other ZX81 sites.  Don't expect to
see any of this any time soon.

@{b}Q. That was a long answer!  Now, what about ZX80 stuff?@{ub}

You'll be lucky.  There's one (yes: one) ZX80 program file in existance
which comes with the DOS Xtender2 (beta) emulator http://www.delhez.demon.nl
and it doesn't work on z81!  You can list it with ZX80LIST, though...

As for other programs, you'll have to type them in.  There's a game called
"Helicopter Landing", which is in an old issue of Sinclair User...

@{b}Q. Was it really possible to control a Nuclear Power Plant with a ZX81?@{ub}

Sir Clive reckoned it was.

@{b}Q. What interface do I need to control a power station?@{ub}

Look, I'm really busy...

@{b}Q. Wait!  I've got lots more questions about the ZX81!@{ub}

Then consult the ZX81 FAQ.  The new official location is on WOS.  It's
quite small compared to other FAQs (most notably the comp.sys.sinclair one,
which is more of a Spectrum FAQ), but I'm sure if you keep asking questions
it'll get bigger.

If you can't find what you want in there, join the ZX81 mailing list, or
try asking the friendly bunch on the newsgroup comp.sys.sinclair.
@endnode

@node Introduction
ZX81Utils was originally released because I had written a P->81 convertor
for Paul Hill (it later turned out that he didn't need it, but that's not
the point), and also had some quick ports of the ZX81 utilities included
with Xtender.

The package was an immense success (yeah, right), basically because xz81 had
not yet been released, and even if it had nobody would have known where to
get it from anyway.

Now a couple of months after its release, and now it works on my A1200, I'm
releasing an enhanced version with better documentation and more tools.  And
the address for xz81 (http://www.lagernet.clara.co.uk)
@endnode

@node Requirements
You don't need much for this.  It should all work on a base A500, with the
exception of:

Pot81        - requires WB2.04
ZX81UtilsGUI - requires WB2.04
               WB3.0 highly recommended, as it expects to find MultiView

ZX80LIST and ZX81LIST prefer the Spectrum.font (included) to be installed,
and the output should be viewed with an ANSI viewer which allow you to
change the font (eg. MultiView)
@endnode

