@endnode

@node ZX81UtilsGUI
ZX81ToolsGUI @{b}must@{ub} be in the same drawer as ZX80LIST, ZX81LIST and
Pot81!

This is a small GUI for the above mentioned programs.

Usage
-----

Click on "Input" and select a file to view or convert.  If you are
attempting conversion, also click on "Output" and enter the filename to save
as.

You can also select an output file in View mode, and in this case it will
create a text file as well as displaying the listing.

To view a listing, toggle the cycle gadget to the appropriate filetype
(either ZX80 or ZX81), and click "View".  The 8081LIST utils do sanity
checks on the files, so a crash @{i}shouldn't@{ui} occur if the cycle gadget
is set incorrectly.

To convert the file, select the conversion direction (P -> 81 or 81 -> P)
and click "Convert".

History
-------

@{b}v1.1 (27.08.2001)@{ub}

Finally fixed the font sensitivity bug
Changed the file requester so it only shows .p .o and .81 files

@endnode

@node Pot81
Introduction
------------

This converts the ZX81 snapshot (or tape image, really) formats .P and .81
between themselves.  At least, I think it does.

The name "Pot81" comes from this being a ".P TO .81" and ".81 TO .P"
program.  PTO81 wasn't right, and there's already a program by that name
anyway.  Pot81 is, therefore, "Pto81" with the "to" part written backwards. 
Cunningly, if you reverse the entire name, it comes out as "18toP" - which
is "81toP" with the "81" part written backwards.  Clever, huh? (well, I
thought so)

Usage
-----

Simply open a shell and type:

Pot81 <input file> <output file>

Pot81 will read the extension of the source file, and convert it to the
other format.  You can tell Pot which format the original is in (a lot of .P
files are actually .81 format) by specifying an additional switch on the
command line.

eg. Pot81 tetris.p tetris.81 81

Will convert the .81 file "tetris.p" into a .P file called "tetris.81".
Confused?

Note that you cannot specify the same filename for source and destination,
and that if output files exist they will be overwritten without prompting.

There is another switch in v1.1 which will make Pot81 output a file
containing a Spectrum-style checksum at the end.  This was implemented for
some reason (although I can't remember why), and may eventually end up as a
.P -> .TAP convertor.
@endnode

@node ZX81LIST
This converts ZX81 program files (.P or .81) to text, complete with ANSI
escape sequences to show inversed text as such.  The block graphics can
be displayed by switching to Spectrum.font when viewing the file - without
it you will get various strange characters to depict the graphics (consult
the Spectrum.font guide)

Usage
-----

ZX81LIST zx81prog.p zx81prog.txt

will convert the ZX81 program file "zx81prog.p" to a text file called
"zx81prog.txt"

It is advisable to then view the output with something like:

MultiView zx81prog.txt FONTNAME Spectrum FONTSIZE 8

If you want to do the reverse, use zxtext2p on Aminet (OS4 only).

@endnode


@node ZX80LIST
This converts ZX80 program files (zx80prog.p or .o) to text, complete with
block graphics (can be viewed by using Spectrum.font when displaying the
file).  Without the Spectrum.font you will get various strange characters to
depict the graphics.

Yes, I know the ZX80 font is significantly different to the ZX81/Spectrum
one.  Also, there are no guarantees that the graphics on the real ZX80
listing and the ZX80LIST one are the same.

Usage
-----

ZX80LIST zx80prog.p zx80prog.txt

will convert the ZX80 program file "zx80prog.p" to a text file called
"zx80prog.txt"

It is advisable to then view the output with something like:

MultiView zx80prog.txt FONTNAME Spectrum FONTSIZE 8

History
-------

@{b}v1.3 (23.08.2001)@{ub}

A modified vesion of v1.2 which will work better on Linux or other systems
where the spectrum.font is not available.
Binary for AmigaDE included.
@endnode

@node P2TXT
This converts ZX81 program files (.P or .81) into ASCII text, without ANSI
or Spectrum.font characters.

It is @{b}not@{ub} written by me!

Usage
-----

P2TXT zx81prog.p

Will display zx81prog.p as text in the current window.  To produce a file,
simply redirect the output.

eg. P2TXT zx81prog.p zx81prog.txt

Will produce a text file called zx81prog.txt

History
-------

This is a newer version recompiled for the Amiga, with one small difference
the pound sign shows as a pound sign (Ł), rather than a hash (#).
@endnode

@node ZXAS
This converts ZXAS2 assembler output to text.

This was @{b}not@{ub} written by me!

I haven't actually ever used this, so it might not even work...!

Usage
-----

ZXAS filename.L filename.TXT

Will convert filename.L to an ASCII file called filename.TXT
@endnode

